===Sources=== ==== Thermal==== * KEPCO (한국전력공사) controls 5 regional gencos who sell via KPX to the grid: * Korea East-West Power (한국동서발전㈜) * Korea Midland Power (한국중부발전㈜) * Korea South-Eastern Power (한국남동발전㈜) * Korea Southern Power (한국남부발전㈜) * Korea Western Power (한국서부발전㈜) [[KOGAS]] (한국가스공사) acts as importer of LNG for the power generators.
==== Cogeneration and steam-heating ==== * [[Korea District Heating Corporation]] (KDHC, 한국지역난방공사㈜) supplies steam and CHP to the Seoul area and Daegu. GS Power and SH Corp are local providers. KDHC is the world's largest [[district heating]] company.
==== Nuclear Power ==== {{main article|Nuclear power in South Korea}} South Korea placed a heavy emphasis on [[nuclear power]] generation. The country's first nuclear power plant, the [[Kori Nuclear Power Plant|Kori Number One]] located near Pusan, which opened in 1977. Eight plants operated in 1987 when atomic power generation was an estimated 71,158 million kilowatts, or 53.1% of total electric power.
==== Renewable energy ==== [[File:SolarGIS-Solar-map-South-Korea-en.png|thumb|upright=0.6|[[Insolation|Solar potential]] map]] The government decision in July 2008 to increase investment in [[renewable energy]] to reduce [[Energy security|reliance]] on foreign oil imports may provide an incentive for conglomerates' solar plans.<ref name="greentechmedia.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.greentechmedia.com/articles/south-korea-to-boost-renewable-energy-investments-by-60-1191.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216145303/http://www.greentechmedia.com/articles/south-korea-to-boost-renewable-energy-investments-by-60-1191.html |archivedate=2008-12-16 |df= }}</ref> The Ministry of Knowledge and Economy said the country intends to spend 194.4 billion won ($193 million) on technologies and projects, including solar, wind and [[biofuel]]s, in 2008.<ref name="greentechmedia.com"/>
South Korea is fast-growing gigawatt-market for [[photovoltaics]] (PV). In 2014, the country ranked among the world-leading [[Growth of photovoltaics#Top 10 ranking of worldwide photovoltaic installation|top-ten installers]] of [[PV systems]]. {{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}
Hydro also comes under [[Korea Hydro & Nuclear Power]] Ltd. (한국수력원자력㈜){{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}
=== Storage === In December 2017, [[Hyundai Electric]] announced a plan to build a 150MW grid storage battery near [[Ulsan]] for [[Korea Zinc]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/business/hyundai-building-150-mw-energy-storage-battery-in-south-korea/article/509427 |title=Hyundai building 150 MW energy storage battery in South Korea |first=Karen |last=Graham |date=7 December 2017 |newspaper=Digital Journal |accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref>
== Global warming == {{See also|Category:Climate change by country}}
According to the Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center [[CDIAC]] South Korea is among the top ten, namely ninth, highest country in [[carbon dioxide]] emissions in the period 1950-2005. The United States (25%), China (10%) and Russia (8%) are the countries with the highest carbon dioxide emissions from 1950-2005.<ref>[[State of the World (book series)|State of the world 2009]], Worldwatch institute 2009, statistics 219-223, CDIAC Carbon dioxide information analysis center (http://www.cdiac.ornl.gov/trends{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }})</ref>
