[[File:Map Iran earthquakes 1990.gif|thumb|Earthquakes in Iran from 1990–2006, by [[United States Geological Survey]]]] [[Iran]] is one of the most seismically active countries in the world, being crossed by several major faults that cover at least 90% of the country.<ref name=BuffaloUniversity>{{cite web|url=http://mceer.buffalo.edu/research/Reconnaissance/Iran6-22-02/ |title=Preliminary Earthquake Reconnaissance Report on the June 22, 2002 Changureh (Avaj), Iran Earthquake |accessdate=December 30, 2008 |publisher=International Institute of Earthquake Engineering and Seismology |date=2002-07-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100325123100/http://mceer.buffalo.edu/research/Reconnaissance/Iran6-22-02/ |archivedate=March 25, 2010 |df= }}</ref> As a result, earthquakes in Iran occur often and are destructive.
== Geology and history == The [[Iranian plateau]] is subject to most types of [[tectonic]] activity, including active [[Fold (geology)|folding]], [[Fault (geology)|faulting]] and [[volcano|volcanic]] eruptions. It is well known for its long history of disastrous earthquake activity. Not only have these earthquakes killed thousands, but they have also led to waste of valuable natural resources.<ref name=Iranian>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranian.com/Iranica/June97/Earthquake/Text2.html|title=100 years; 126,000 deaths|author=Manuel Berberian|publisher=The Iranian}}</ref> Since 1900, at least 126,000 fatalities have resulted from earthquakes in Iran.<ref name=Iranian/>
